ovided by a properly functioning community of friends and relations. People were able to learn social skills long before there were schools. What schools actually promote, of course, is not &quot;social skill&quot; but social conformity, social obedience, and social subservience to an unelected &quot;authority&quot; external to the family. Home schooling, on the other hand, promotes independence, especially independence from the state - which is the reason totalitarians hate home schooling so much, and ban it so happily. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="800" language="en" documentId="887" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="PyrrhoHuxley" date="06 November 2009 3:09pm" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/6744096" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="32" thumbsDown="0" origId="887" notes="" title="Ridiculous rules for home schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="240"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="241" end="800"/><types:PersuasivenessAnnotationMetaData xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" annotator="annotator1" isPersuasive="true" labelDetailed="P1" isGold="false" comment="&quot;You don't need school for this, since this can be provided by a properly functioning community of friends and relations.&quot;&#13;&#10;&#13;&#10;&quot;Home schooling, on the other hand, promotes independence, especially independence from the state&quot;" annotationBatchName="batch2-690documents" conflictResolvingAnnotation="false"/><types:PersuasivenessAnnotationMetaData xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" annotator="annotator3" isPersuasive="true" labelDetailed="P1" isGold="false" annotationBatchName="batch2-690documents" conflictResolvingAnnotation="false"/><types:PersuasivenessAnnotationMetaData xmi:id="71" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" isPersuasive="true" isGold="true" annotationBatchName="batch2-690documents" conflictR